{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context / problem\n\nR7 (child `b1a4`) shipped `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/gate_eval_instrumentation.py`,\nwhich computes per-criterion `blocking_fp_proxy` + `advisory_application_rate` by joining each\nreviewed ticket's **outcome-corpus** row (post-claim edit class, reopen count, force-close â€” mined\nfrom the `tickets` orphan branch's git objects by `mine_outcome_corpus.py`) to the ticket's\n`REVIEW_RESULT` sidecar findings. That join is the source of its signal and its cost: it needs a\nfull git-object walk of the tickets branch per refresh, so it is a periodic batch job, not a cheap\nstanding recorder, and its FP signal is the post-hoc force-close/reopen fact.\n\n**Beneficiary + problem.** The epic's own dogfood-monitoring plan (this epic's success criteria and\n`docs/plan-review-gate.md` \"Blocking-FP-proxy demotion\") says new criteria enter at **advisory**\nposture and are watched for promotion/demotion via per-criterion dogfood metrics. As R1/R3/R4 ship\nnew advisory criteria, the gate maintainer needs those criteria monitored **automatically, at zero\nmarginal LLM cost, without per-criterion wiring**, and needs a *detection* signal (does the\ncriterion catch real, acted-on defects?) that R7 does not provide. Today there is no standing,\nsidecar-native recorder that accumulates per-criterion firing history and computes a\ndetection/blocking-FP proxy without the outcome-corpus git-walk.\n\n## What this delivers (DISTINCT from and complementary to R7 â€” not a duplicate)\n\nA **standing per-criterion effectiveness recorder** whose signal source is the sidecar\n**re-review history ALONE** â€” no outcome corpus, no git-object walk, so it is cheap and incremental.\nConcretely:\n\n1. **Recorder** â€” a new harness `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/criterion_effectiveness.py`\n   that reads the persisted `REVIEW_RESULT` sidecars and appends one lean **firing row per\n   (review-round, finding)** into an append-only, **prune-immune** ledger\n   `runs/criterion_firings.jsonl`. Each row uses **short keys** (compact + jq-friendly), documented\n   in the harness docstring: `t`=ticket_id, `ts`=review_ts_ns (int), `r`=round_uuid, `v`=verdict,\n   `c`=criteria (list), `n`=norm_id, `u`=fix_unit_key, `d`=decision, `s`=severity, `p`=priority,\n   `x`=drop_reason. **Where the envelope identity comes from:** the review's `ts_ns` and `round_uuid`\n   are parsed from the sidecar **filename** (`<ts_ns>-<uuid>-REVIEW_RESULT.json`, the format\n   `event_append` writes and that `sidecar.all_review_results` orders by) â€” the recorder mirrors\n   `all_review_results`'s file-enumeration + v1/v2 schema guard but reads the filename directly,\n   because `all_review_results` returns only the payload `data` body and drops the event envelope\n   (so ts/uuid are NOT available from it). The per-finding fields (`c`/`n`/`d`/`s`/`p`/`x`) come from\n   the payload's `findings[]`; `u`=`fix_unit_key` is computed via the production\n   `sidecar.fix_unit_key`. It **auto-includes any criterion id it sees** (no per-criterion\n   registration). `--backfill` seeds the ledger from the entire existing corpus; the default\n   `--record` mode is incremental (appends only reviews whose filename `ts_ns` exceeds the ledger's\n   max recorded `ts`), and re-running EITHER mode is **idempotent** (dedup key\n   `(t, ts, r, n)` = ticket + review_ts + round_uuid + norm_id â€” so `--backfill` is also\n   re-runnable without duplication). The ledger is prune-immune because the sidecar's own retention\n   prune caps history at `RETAIN_PER_TICKET=50` rounds/ticket â€” a durable firing ledger captures\n   firings before that prune, which is the standing recorder's reason to exist.\n\n2. **`--report`** â€” computes, per criterion over a trailing `--window` (the N most-recently-reviewed\n   tickets, ranked by each ticket's max `review_ts`; windowing per-ticket keeps each ticket's full\n   round history intact, which the disposition logic below needs), from the ledger ALONE:\n   - `detection_proxy` = fraction of the criterion's distinct blocking fix-units (keyed by\n     `fix_unit_key`, criteria-free, attributed to the criterion via the firing's `c` criteria list)\n     that the ticket later **remediated to a PASS** â€” i.e. the fix-unit is a blocking firing in some\n     round and is **absent from the ticket's latest round AND that latest round's verdict is PASS**.\n     A latest round whose verdict is `BLOCK` or `INDETERMINATE` is treated as **non-PASS**\n     (conservative: not counted as remediated). Denominator = \"resolvable\" blocking fix-units (a\n     round exists after the fix-unit's first blocking appearance, so a disposition is observable).\n     This is a caught-then-fixed \"true-positive-ish\" proxy R7 does not compute at all.\n   - `blocking_fp_proxy` = fraction of the criterion's distinct blocking fix-units the gate later\n     **de-escalated** (in a round after its first blocking appearance the same fix-unit is found but\n     no longer surfaced as blocking â€” decision `dropped`) and never remediated to a PASS. The gate's\n     own re-review reversed the earlier block, a conservative within-review FP lower bound. The\n     `dropped` decision deliberately subsumes BOTH a Pass-3 threshold drop and the novelty/completion\n     convergence floors: an empirical check of the existing corpus shows the floors are inert by\n     default (every `dropped` finding carries `drop_reason` null), so a floor-only signal would be\n     structurally dead â€” keying off `decision == \"dropped\"` is what gives the proxy real signal now\n     (the per-firing `drop_reason` is still recorded to LABEL floor-driven drops for future floor-era\n     segmentation). This is a **deliberately DIFFERENT metric from R7's** same-named proxy: R7 counts\n     blocking findings whose ticket was later force-closed/reopened (an outcome-corpus, post-hoc\n     signal); this counts blocking fix-units the gate reversed across re-review rounds (a\n     sidecar-only, within-review signal). The two are complementary FP lenses with different base\n     rates, not a redefinition of R7's â€” R7's harness and metric are untouched, and R7's 10% alarm\n     threshold is calibrated to ITS force-close proxy, not transferable as-is to this one.\n   - `sample_counts` = the denominators (distinct blocking fix-units, resolvable fix-units, advisory\n     firings, distinct tickets, total firings) so a rate is `null` (not fabricated) when its\n     denominator is 0.\n   `--report` writes `runs/criterion_effectiveness.json` and auto-includes **every** criterion id in\n   the ledger. **`--report` reads the committed ledger as-is and never auto-records**; the\n   `--no-refresh` flag is an explicit alias for that default (kept for symmetry with R7's\n   `--no-refresh` and to make AC3's proving command self-documenting), so the report is deterministic\n   over the committed artifact whether or not `--no-refresh` is passed. To refresh first, run\n   `--record` then `--report` as two steps.\n\n3. **Wiring / cadence.** The standing invocation is documented (a periodic `--record` incremental\n   append, session-log-style, then `--report`), following R7's precedent (a harness under\n   `docs/experiments/` + a thin CI unit test of its pure functions), and `docs/plan-review-gate.md`\n   records the production emit-time hook (`sidecar.emit` in\n   `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/__init__.py`) as the future integration seam. This deliberately does\n   NOT modify the review hot path, keeping the verdict byte-identical and the emit best-effort-safe.\n\n**Approach rationale (why this shape, alternatives weighed).** A documented harness + standing\n`--record` was chosen over a production emit-hook because it keeps the review hot path byte-identical\nand best-effort-safe, matches the R7 precedent (so the two dogfood jobs read alike), avoids growing\nany module-size-pinned production file, and the append-only ledger is prune-immune where reading\nsidecars live at report time is not (the 50-round retention prune drops older firings). The\nsidecar-history-only signal was chosen over re-using R7's outcome corpus specifically to make the\nrecorder standing and $0 â€” reusing that corpus would re-introduce the git-walk cost and duplicate\nR7's metric rather than complement it. This is deterministic instrumentation over data that already\nexists: **no LLM call, no batch eval, no new eval spend.**\n\n## Scope â€” files\n\n- NEW `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/criterion_effectiveness.py` â€” recorder + report\n  (target 200â€“500 LOC; a docs/experiments harness, so not collected by pytest and not scanned by\n  the src/rebar module-size gate).\n- NEW `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/criterion_firings.jsonl` â€” the append-only firing\n  ledger, backfilled from the existing corpus (committed; CI-visible, since `.tickets-tracker/` is\n  git-ignored and absent in CI).\n- NEW `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/criterion_effectiveness.json` â€” the metrics artifact\n  over the EXISTING corpus (committed proof it works now).\n- NEW `tests/unit/test_criterion_effectiveness.py` â€” deterministic unit tests of the pure functions\n  (loads the harness by path, exactly as `tests/unit/test_gate_eval_classifier.py` loads R7's).\n- EDIT `docs/plan-review-gate.md` â€” add the standing-recorder + advisoryâ†’blocking promotion-gate\n  protocol (the section R1/R3/R4 reference), stating the R7 distinction.\n- EDIT `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/README.md` â€” usage under the existing \"Gate-eval\n  instrumentation (R7 â€¦)\" material.\n\n**Reused existing symbols (verified present).** `rebar.llm.plan_review.sidecar.all_review_results`,\n`sidecar.fix_unit_key`, `sidecar.norm_id`, `sidecar.EVENT_TYPE`, `sidecar.RETAIN_PER_TICKET` (all in\n`src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py`); the R7 harness `gate_eval_instrumentation.py` and its test\n`tests/unit/test_gate_eval_classifier.py` (the path-load pattern). Firing fingerprints are computed\nvia the production `sidecar.fix_unit_key` / stored `norm_id` â€” this recorder does NOT re-implement\nfingerprint logic.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] **AC1 (recorder + auto-inclusion).** `criterion_effectiveness.py --record --backfill` reads\n  the live sidecar corpus and writes `runs/criterion_firings.jsonl`, one JSON row per\n  (review-round, finding), auto-including every criterion id present. PROVE:\n  `python docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/criterion_effectiveness.py --record --backfill`\n  then `test $(wc -l < docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/criterion_firings.jsonl) -gt 5000` and\n  `test $(jq -r '.c[]' docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/criterion_firings.jsonl | sort -u | wc -l) -ge 30`.\n- [ ] **AC2 (idempotent incremental append).** Re-running the recorder appends no duplicate firings\n  (dedup key `(ticket, review_ts, round_uuid, norm_id)`). PROVE:\n  `N=$(wc -l < â€¦/criterion_firings.jsonl); python â€¦/criterion_effectiveness.py --record --backfill;\n  test $(wc -l < â€¦/criterion_firings.jsonl) -eq \"$N\"`.\n- [ ] **AC3 (`--report` over trailing window, auto-includes every criterion).**\n  `criterion_effectiveness.py --report --no-refresh --window 400` reads the committed ledger and\n  writes `runs/criterion_effectiveness.json` with, per criterion, `detection_proxy`,\n  `blocking_fp_proxy`, and `sample_counts` (integer denominators). PROVE: run it, then\n  `test $(jq 'keys|length' â€¦/criterion_effectiveness.json) -ge 30` and\n  `jq -e 'all(.[]; has(\"detection_proxy\") and has(\"blocking_fp_proxy\") and (.sample_counts.blocking_fix_units|type==\"number\"))' â€¦/criterion_effectiveness.json`.\n- [ ] **AC4 (deterministic pure functions, CI-tested).** `tests/unit/test_criterion_effectiveness.py`\n  asserts, on synthetic fixtures: (a) `detection_proxy` counts a blocking fix-unit remediated to a\n  later PASS round; (b) `blocking_fp_proxy` counts a blocking fix-unit later floor-suppressed\n  (`drop_reason` set) and never remediated; (c) a criterion id unseen by any prior fixture is\n  auto-included in the report; (d) `--window` bounds the tickets considered; (e) a criterion with a\n  zero denominator yields `null` (not a fabricated `0.0`) for that proxy. PROVE:\n  `python -m pytest tests/unit/test_criterion_effectiveness.py -q` exits 0.\n- [ ] **AC5 (works over EXISTING data NOW, not future data).** The committed\n  `runs/criterion_effectiveness.json` is computed over the existing sidecar corpus and carries real\n  values: at least one criterion has a non-null `detection_proxy` AND at least one has a non-null\n  `blocking_fp_proxy`. PROVE:\n  `test $(jq '[.[]|select(.detection_proxy!=null)]|length' â€¦/criterion_effectiveness.json) -ge 1` and\n  `test $(jq '[.[]|select(.blocking_fp_proxy!=null)]|length' â€¦/criterion_effectiveness.json) -ge 1`.\n- [ ] **AC6 (docs: standing cadence + promotion-gate protocol + R7 distinction).**\n  `docs/plan-review-gate.md` gains a section documenting the standing recorder, the\n  advisoryâ†’blocking promotion gate that R1/R3/R4 reference (auto-inclusion = zero per-criterion\n  wiring), and how this recorder is distinct from R7's outcome-corpus metric; the experiments README\n  documents the `--record`/`--report` usage. PROVE:\n  `grep -q \"criterion_effectiveness\" docs/plan-review-gate.md && grep -q \"promotion\" docs/plan-review-gate.md`\n  and `grep -q \"criterion_effectiveness\" docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/README.md`.\n- [ ] **AC7 (zero-LLM + gates green).** The recorder makes no LLM/agent call (deterministic only),\n  and the change passes lint, typecheck, and the module-size gate with no pinned file grown. PROVE:\n  `! grep -iE \"anthropic|ANTHROPIC_API_KEY|invoke_(model|agent)|runner\\\\.run\" docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/criterion_effectiveness.py`\n  and `make lint` and `python -m pytest tests/unit/test_module_size_contract.py -q` exit 0.\n\n## Testing plan\n\nDeterministic unit tests only (no LLM). The heavy detection/FP/window logic is proven on small\nin-memory fixtures with known round sequences (RED-then-GREEN for each rule); a lightweight\ncommitted-corpus assertion proves non-triviality over real data. The `--record`/`--report` IO paths\nare exercised by the AC proving commands this session against the existing corpus (the recorder's\nlive-store read mirrors R7's `--verify-repro` manual-verification posture; the committed ledger is\nthe CI-visible artifact, since `.tickets-tracker/` is git-ignored and absent in CI).\n\n## Sequencing / dependencies\n\nNo file overlap with R1â€“R6 (this adds a NEW harness, NEW runs artifacts, a NEW test, and appends\ndoc sections). It complements R7 (`b1a4`, already landed) and is referenced by R1/R3/R4's advisory\ncriteria via auto-inclusion. Lands through Gerrit (LLM-Review +1 AND Verified +1), then closes."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784398677025581001,"uuid":"fdedc8a2-2867-4fb2-9a4d-caba73fd71f3"}